% ─── INLINE VS DISPLAY ────────────────────────────────────────────────────

% This is a cassilda label -- the source goes inside
@label inline_vs_display
    Math can appear inline or in display mode. Inline math is
    wrapped in single dollar signs and flows with the text:
    the equation $a^2 + b^2 = c^2$ sits inside a sentence.

    Display math is wrapped in double dollar signs and gets
    its own centered block. The implicit spacing below and above
    math is controlled by \cmd{setmathabove} and \cmd{setmathbelow}.

    $$ a^2 + b^2 = c^2 $$

    Use inline for small expressions mentioned in passing.
    Use display for anything you want to stand on its own.
@end

% This is a cassilda reference -- renders (or updates) the specified label under itself
