│  These are equivalent:
│  
│                                            𝑎̂     𝑎̂
│                               𝑥     𝑥     𝑦     𝑦
│                                𝐯     𝐯
│  
│  More examples:
│  
│                                        𝑛 + 1
│                             𝑎         𝑏         𝑥
│                              𝑖 + 1               max

% ─── FRACTIONS ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

@label fractions
    \cmd{frac} builds a fraction with a horizontal bar.
    \cmd{dfrac} and \cmd{tfrac} are accepted as aliases.
    Fractions nest naturally and to infinite depth.
    Long math source can be written over multiple lines with
    no effect on typesetting:

    $$
        \frac{a}{b},\,
        \frac{x+1}{x-1},\,
        a + \frac{b}{c} + d,\,
        \frac{\frac{a}{b}}{\frac{c}{d}}
    $$

    
    In vacuum, Maxwell's equations give the wave equation:
    $$ \nabla^2\mathbf{E} = \mu_0\epsilon_0\frac{\partial^2\mathbf{E}}{\partial t^2} $$

    The speed of light emerges:
    $$ c = \frac{1}{\sqrt{\mu_0\epsilon_0}} = 299792458 \text{ m/s} $$    
@end

@cassilda: fractions
│  \𝑓𝑟𝑎𝑐 builds a fraction with a horizontal  bar. \𝑑𝑓𝑟𝑎𝑐 and \𝑡𝑓𝑟𝑎𝑐 are accepted
│  as aliases.  Fractions nest naturally  and to infinite depth. Long math source
│  can be written over multiple lines with no effect on typesetting:
│  
│                                                        𝑎
│                                                       ───
│                       𝑎      𝑥 + 1         𝑏           𝑏
│                      ───,   ───────,  𝑎 + ─── + 𝑑,   ─────
│                       𝑏      𝑥 − 1         𝑐           𝑐
│                                                       ───
│                                                        𝑑
│  
│  In vacuum, Maxwell’s equations give the wave equation:
│  
│                                              2
│                                  2          ∂ 𝐄
│                                 ∇ 𝐄 = μ ε  ─────
│                                        0 0    2
│                                             ∂𝑡
│  
│  The speed of light emerges:
│  
│                                  1
│                           𝑐 = ─────── = 299792458 m/s
│                                 ⎽⎽⎽⎽
│                                √μ ε
│                                  0 0

% ─── ROOTS ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

@label roots
    \cmd{sqrt} makes a square root.  An optional argument
    gives the nth root: $\sqrt[3]{x}$.  Roots can infinitely
    nest just as fractions:

    $$ \sqrt{x} $$
    $$ \sqrt{x+1} $$
    $$ \sqrt[3]{x} $$
    $$ \sqrt[n]{x^2 + y^2} $$
    $$ \sqrt{\sqrt{x}} $$

    Complicated fraction:

    $$ \frac{\sqrt[3]{\frac{\frac{x+y}{\frac{1}{2}} \cdot \sum_{k=1}^{n} k^2 }{a - 
        b}}}{\sqrt[3]{\frac{\frac{x+y}{\frac{1}{2}}}{a - b}}} $$

    ASCII version:

    \setunicode{false}
    
    $$ \frac{\sqrt[3]{\frac{\frac{x+y}{\frac{1}{2}} \cdot \sum_{k=1}^{n} k^2 }{a - 
            b}}}{\sqrt[3]{\frac{\frac{x+y}{\frac{1}{2}}}{a - b}}} $$
@end

@cassilda: roots
