% ─── PARENTHESES AND GROUPING ────────────────────────────────────────────

@label parens
    Parentheses, brackets, and braces.  Curly braces need
    escaping with backslash.  Absolute values use pipes or
    explicit commands:

    $$ (a + b) $$
    $$ [a + b] $$
    $$ \{a + b\} $$
    $$ |x| $$
    $$ \Vert x \Vert $$
@end

@cassilda: parens
│  Parentheses,  brackets, and braces. Curly braces need escaping with backslash.
│  Absolute values use pipes or explicit commands:
│  
│                                     (𝑎 + 𝑏)
│  
│                                     [𝑎 + 𝑏]
│  
│                                     {𝑎 + 𝑏}
│  
│                                       |𝑥|
│  
│                                       ║𝑥║

% ─── AUTO-SCALING DELIMITERS ─────────────────────────────────────────────

@label autoscale
    \cmd{left} and \cmd{right} make delimiters grow to match
    their contents.  This is essential when wrapping fractions
    or other tall constructs:

    $$ \left( \frac{a}{b} \right)\quad
       \left[ \frac{a}{b} \right]\quad
       \left| \frac{a}{b} \right| $$

    $$\cdots$$

    $$\left( \left(a\cdot b\right) \frac{\frac{1}{2}}{\left(\frac{a}{b} \right)}
       + \left(\frac{1}{2e^x}\right) \right)$$

    Use \cmd{left}. or \cmd{right}. for invisible (null) delimiters.
    This is essential for evaluation bars and one-sided brackets:

    $$ \left.\frac{df}{dx}\right|_{x=0} $$
    $$ \left.\frac{x^3}{3}\right|_0^1 $$
    $$ \left(\frac{a}{b}\right. $$

    Use \cmd{middle} inside \cmd{left}...\cmd{right} for scaled
    interior delimiters (e.g.\ set builder notation, conditional
    probability):

    $$ \left( \frac{a}{b} \middle| \frac{c}{d} \right) $$

@end

