% ─── OVERSET AND UNDERSET ────────────────────────────────────────────────

@label overset
    \cmd{overset} places an annotation above a base symbol.
    \cmd{underset} places it below.  \cmd{stackrel} is an
    alias for \cmd{overset}:

    $$ A\,\overset{n}{=}\,B$$
    $$ \underset{x \to 0}{\lim} f(x) $$
    $$ A\stackrel{\text{def}}{=}B $$
@end

@cassilda: overset
│  \𝑜𝑣𝑒𝑟𝑠𝑒𝑡 places an annotation  above a base symbol. \𝑢𝑛𝑑𝑒𝑟𝑠𝑒𝑡 places it below.
│  \𝑠𝑡𝑎𝑐𝑘𝑟𝑒𝑙 is an alias for \𝑜𝑣𝑒𝑟𝑠𝑒𝑡:
│  
│                                        𝑛
│                                      𝐴 = 𝐵
│  
│                                     lim 𝑓(𝑥)
│                                    𝑥 → 0
│  
│                                       def
│                                      𝐴 = 𝐵

% ─── PRIMES ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

@label primes
    Primes (derivative notation) use the apostrophe:

    $$ f'(x) $$
    $$ f''(x) $$
    $$ f'''(x) $$
    $$ f^{(n)}(x) $$

    Quotient Rule:
    $$ \frac{d}{dx}\left[\frac{f(x)}{g(x)}\right] = \frac{f'(x)g(x) - f(x)g'(x)}{[g(x)]^2} $$

    The second derivative measures the rate of change of the first derivative:
    $$ f''(x) = \frac{d^2y}{dx^2} = \frac{d}{dx}\left(\frac{dy}{dx}\right) $$    
@end

@cassilda: primes
│  Primes (derivative notation) use the apostrophe:
│  
│                                      𝑓′(𝑥)
│  
│                                      𝑓″(𝑥)
│  
│                                      𝑓‴(𝑥)
│  
│                                      (𝑛)
│                                     𝑓   (𝑥)
│  
│  Quotient Rule:
│  
│                     𝑑   ⎡  𝑓(𝑥)  ⎤    𝑓′(𝑥)𝑔(𝑥) − 𝑓(𝑥)𝑔′(𝑥)
│                    ──── ⎢ ────── ⎥ = ───────────────────────
│                     𝑑𝑥  ⎣  𝑔(𝑥)  ⎦                 2
│                                              [𝑔(𝑥)]
│  
│  The second derivative measures the rate of change of the first derivative:
│  
│                                    2
│                                   𝑑 𝑦     𝑑   ⎛  𝑑𝑦  ⎞
│                          𝑓″(𝑥) = ───── = ──── ⎜ ──── ⎟
│                                     2     𝑑𝑥  ⎝  𝑑𝑥  ⎠
│                                   𝑑𝑥

% ─── MATH FONTS ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

@label math_fonts
    Special font families for different mathematical objects:

    Bold for vectors and matrices: $\mathbf{A}\mathbf{x} = \mathbf{b}$

    Blackboard bold for number sets:

    $$ \mathbb{N} \quad \mathbb{Z} \quad \mathbb{Q} \quad \mathbb{R} \quad \mathbb{C} $$

    Calligraphic / script for operators and spaces:

    $$ \mathcal{L} \quad \mathcal{F} \quad \mathcal{O}\left(n^2\right) $$

    Fraktur for Lie algebras and ideals:

    $$ \mathfrak{g} \quad \mathfrak{h} \quad \mathfrak{su}(2) $$

    Sans-serif for categories and special objects:

    $$ \mathsf{Set} \quad \mathsf{Top} \quad \mathsf{Grp} $$

    Bold symbols including Greek and operators (via \cmd{boldsymbol}):

    $$ \boldsymbol{\alpha} + \boldsymbol{\beta} = \boldsymbol{\gamma} $$

    Bold nabla and partial:

    $$ \boldsymbol{\nabla} f \quad \boldsymbol{\partial} $$
@end

